{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525121"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14057"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14057"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.21,0.06,0.37,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6711"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43931"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up of iron deficiency anaemia. He was initially diagnosed three months ago when he presented with fatigue. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Initial investigations three months ago revealed a haemoglobin of 110 g/L (130-180) and ferritin of 10 \u00b5g/L (30-300). Coeliac serology was negative. Gastroscopy demonstrated \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E gastritis, which was treated with triple therapy and successfully eradicated. His colonoscopy was normal with good views obtained. He has been taking oral iron supplements for the past three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERepeat blood tests show a haemoglobin of 115 g/L (130-180) and ferritin of 15 \u00b5g/L (30-300).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat iron studies in three months","Repeat gastroscopy and colonoscopy","CT abdomen and pelvis","Capsule endoscopy","Bone marrow biopsy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the most appropriate next investigation is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapsule endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has a persistent iron deficiency anaemia despite treatment of \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection and iron supplementation. Both gastroscopy and colonoscopy have been performed without identifying a clear source of blood loss. It is possible that the source of blood loss is out of reach of both the gastroscope and the colonoscope - ie the small bowel. Capsule endoscopy is the preferred next step to evaluate the small bowel, which is not accessible by conventional endoscopy. Urinary tract investigations may also be appropriate to assess for other sites of blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat iron studies in three months\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate at this stage. The patient has already shown minimal improvement despite three months of iron supplementation, indicating a need for further investigation rather than continued monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat gastroscopy and colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to yield new information at this stage, given that the previous gastroscopy identified and treated \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection and good views were obtained during colonoscopy. The persisting iron deficiency anaemia suggests that there may be another source of blood loss that was not visible on initial endoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered, but it is less sensitive than capsule endoscopy for detecting small bowel lesions that might cause occult bleeding. CT would be more appropriate if there were concerns about extra-intestinal pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone marrow biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that is not indicated at this stage. It would be considered if there were suspicions of a primary bone marrow disorder, which is unlikely given the clear evidence of iron deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Persistent iron deficiency anaemia despite iron supplementation warrants further investigation to identify occult bleeding sources.","Capsule endoscopy should be considered to investigate for small bowel causes of ongoing iron deficiency anaemia when gastroscopy and colonoscopy are non-diagnostic."],"references":["Snook J, Bhala N, Beales ILP, et al. British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines for the management of iron deficiency anaemia in adults. Gut 2021;70:2030-2051."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14057"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T19:51:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T19